		<div class="post" id="post-1453928">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,1453928)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-1453928">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/tl333s" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1304786); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1304786&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610251562" alt="TL333s" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1304786)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/tl333s" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1304786); return false;" >TL333s</a></span> <span class="odate time_1337467287 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">19 May 2012 22:41</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1453928">
									

<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">Some&nbsp;corrections</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<blockquote>
<p>It was mostly heard over intercoms, or through the grape vines</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Normally, it's just &quot;grape vine&quot;. Not sure if that's cultural, but worth pointing out.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>saying he was here “on authority of the Department of Justice” asking us the same question each</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I know you Brits have weird dialogue formatting, but that still needs a comma after Justice. And while I could swing &quot;lifers all&quot;, that would sound better as &quot;asking us each the same question&quot;.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Since then, we've not had to leave the cells, do hard labour, or worry about getting shanked.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Americans in this instance prefer to put the not with the have, so &quot;we haven't had to&quot;. I won't rag on the spelling, because that identifies you rather than the narrator.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>1st April</p>
</blockquote>
<p>April 1st. Note that &quot;31st of March&quot; earlier was fine.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Will we hear from our little friend from the supermax?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Note that you capitalized &quot;supermax&quot; earlier.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>through wish he ushered us.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Unless you want your narrator to come off as maybe more educated than your average criminal, this comes off really stilted. (&quot;which he ushered us through&quot; would suffice.) Same goes for &quot;what we found was definitely not our breakfast&quot; in the next sentence. He kind of starts waxing poetic near the end here.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>as is the cube was being unfolded.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This looks like a typo.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>We never even had the chance to dodge, or run this thing.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Think you meant &quot;outrun&quot;.</p>
<p>But yeah. It all comes off as simple turns of phrase that work in one dialect of English and not the other. :)</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

							</div>

								
					
